{"chunks": ["Operating Systems - Introduction An operating system (OS) is system software that manages computer hardware and software resources and provides common services for computer programs. Key Functions of an Operating System: 1. Process Management - The OS handles the creation, scheduling, and termination of processes. 2. Memory Management - The OS manages the allocation and deallocation of memory space to programs. 3. File System Management - The OS controls how data is stored and retrieved on storage devices. 4. Device Management - The OS manages communication between software and hardware devices via drivers. 5. Security and Access Control - The OS enforces permissions and protects resources from unauthorized access. Types of Operating Systems: - Batch OS: Executes jobs in batches without user interaction (e.g., early IBM systems). - Time-Sharing OS: Multiple users share system resources simultaneously (e.g., Unix). - Distributed OS: Manages a group of independent computers and makes them appear as a single system. - Real-Time OS (RTOS): Processes data within strict time constraints (e.g., embedded systems in cars or medical devices). - Mobile OS: Designed for mobile devices (e.g., Android, iOS). Examples of Operating Systems: - Windows: Widely used desktop OS by Microsoft. - Linux: Open-source OS used in servers, desktops, and embedded systems. - macOS: Apple's desktop OS based on Unix. - Android: Mobile OS based on the Linux kernel. The Kernel: The kernel is the core component of an OS. It operates in privileged mode (kernel mode) and has direct access to hardware. It acts as a bridge between applications and hardware. User Mode vs Kernel Mode: - User Mode: Applications run here with restricted access to hardware. - Kernel Mode: The OS kernel runs here with full hardware access. - A system call is how a user-mode program requests a service from the kernel.", "Process Life Cycle A process is a program in execution. It is an active entity, unlike a program which is a passive set of instructions stored on disk. Process vs Program: - A program is a static set of instructions (a file on disk). - A process is a running instance of a program. The same program can spawn multiple processes. Process States: A process goes through several states during its lifetime: 1. New: The process is being created. Resources are being allocated. 2. Ready: The process is loaded into memory and waiting to be assigned to the CPU. 3. Running: The process is currently being executed by the CPU. 4. Waiting (Blocked): The process is waiting for some event (e.g., I/O completion, a signal). 5. Terminated (Exit): The process has finished execution and resources are being deallocated. State Transitions: - New \u2192 Ready: Process is admitted to the ready queue. - Ready \u2192 Running: The scheduler dispatches the process to the CPU. - Running \u2192 Waiting: Process requests I/O or waits for an event. - Waiting \u2192 Ready: The I/O operation or event completes. - Running \u2192 Ready: Process is preempted (interrupted by the scheduler, e.g., time slice expires). - Running \u2192 Terminated: Process completes execution or is killed. Process Control Block (PCB): Each process is represented in the OS by a Process Control Block (PCB), also called a Task Control Block. The PCB contains: - Process ID (PID): Unique identifier for the process. - Process State: Current state (new, ready, running, waiting, terminated). - Program Counter (PC): Address of the next instruction to execute. - CPU Registers: Contents of all CPU registers for this process. - Memory Management Info: Page tables, segment tables, memory limits. - I/O Status: List of open files and I/O devices assigned to the process. - Accounting Info: CPU time used, time limits, job numbers. Context Switching: When the CPU switches from one process to another, the OS saves the state of the old process into its PCB and loads the state of the new process from its PCB. This is called a context switch. Context switching has overhead \u2014 the CPU does no useful work during the switch. CPU Scheduling: The scheduler decides which process in the ready queue gets the CPU next. Types of schedulers: - Long-term scheduler (Job scheduler): Controls which processes are admitted to the ready queue from the job", "switch. Context switching has overhead \u2014 the CPU does no useful work during the switch. CPU Scheduling: The scheduler decides which process in the ready queue gets the CPU next. Types of schedulers: - Long-term scheduler (Job scheduler): Controls which processes are admitted to the ready queue from the job pool. - Short-term scheduler (CPU scheduler): Selects which ready process gets the CPU next. Runs very frequently. - Medium-term scheduler: Handles swapping \u2014 temporarily removing processes from memory (swapping out) and reintroducing them later (swapping in).", "Process Scheduling Algorithms CPU scheduling determines the order in which processes get CPU time. The goal is to maximize CPU utilization and throughput while minimizing waiting time and response time. Scheduling Criteria: - CPU Utilization: Keep the CPU as busy as possible. - Throughput: Number of processes completed per unit time. - Turnaround Time: Total time from submission to completion of a process. - Waiting Time: Total time a process spends in the ready queue. - Response Time: Time from submission until the first response is produced. Common Scheduling Algorithms: 1. First-Come, First-Served (FCFS): - Processes are scheduled in the order they arrive. - Simple but can cause the convoy effect: short processes wait behind long ones. - Non-preemptive. 2. Shortest Job First (SJF): - The process with the shortest next CPU burst is scheduled first. - Optimal in terms of minimizing average waiting time. - Difficult to implement because CPU burst length is not always known in advance. - Can be preemptive (Shortest Remaining Time First - SRTF) or non-preemptive. 3. Round Robin (RR): - Each process gets a fixed time slice called a quantum (e.g., 10ms). - After the quantum expires, the process is preempted and moved to the back of the ready queue. - Fair and good for time-sharing systems. - Performance depends heavily on the size of the quantum. 4. Priority Scheduling: - Each process is assigned a priority. The highest priority process gets the CPU first. - Can be preemptive or non-preemptive. - Problem: Starvation \u2014 low priority processes may never get CPU time. - Solution: Aging \u2014 gradually increase the priority of waiting processes. 5. Multilevel Queue Scheduling: - The ready queue is divided into multiple queues (e.g., foreground and background). - Each queue has its own scheduling algorithm. - Processes are permanently assigned to a queue. 6. Multilevel Feedback Queue: - Similar to multilevel queue but processes can move between queues. - A process using too much CPU time is moved to a lower-priority queue. - Most flexible and most complex scheduling algorithm. - Used in most modern operating systems. Preemptive vs Non-Preemptive Scheduling: - Non-preemptive: Once a process starts running, it runs until it finishes or blocks. (e.g., FCFS, SJF) - Preemptive: The OS can interrupt a running process and give the CPU to another. (e.g., Round Robin, SRTF)", "Scheduling: - Non-preemptive: Once a process starts running, it runs until it finishes or blocks. (e.g., FCFS, SJF) - Preemptive: The OS can interrupt a running process and give the CPU to another. (e.g., Round Robin, SRTF)"], "embeddings": [[-0.03472470864653587, 0.020116329193115234, -0.016184259206056595, -0.015025630593299866, 0.04401056468486786, -0.06761565804481506, 0.057955849915742874, 0.09561434388160706, 0.036595895886421204, 0.04279661551117897, 0.018142078071832657, 0.041726961731910706, 0.014669021591544151, -0.023667389526963234, 0.015184484422206879, -0.08946779370307922, 0.005077345762401819, -0.09013064205646515, -0.049029391258955, 0.006001063622534275, 0.0696549192070961, 